<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>When the economy is in a liquidity trap, why might the Fed turn to quantitative easing?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">To raise interest rates above zero</option>
            <option letter="b">To directly affect long-term interest rates when short-term rates are at zero</option>
            <option letter="c">To reduce the money supply</option>
            <option letter="d">To increase bank reserve requirements</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>In a liquidity trap, when short-term interest rates are at zero, traditional monetary policy becomes ineffective. The Fed may use quantitative easing (buying long-term securities) to directly influence longer-term interest rates and stimulate the economy through other channels.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
